<!-- ── FORMULA ── -->
<section class="content-section reveal">
  <h2>The Formula</h2>
  <p>Single discount:</p>
  <div class="formula-box">
    Final Price = Original Price &times; (1 &minus; Discount &divide; 100)
  </div>
  <p>Double (stacked) discount:</p>
  <div class="formula-box">
    Final Price = Original Price &times; (1 &minus; D1 &divide; 100) &times; (1 &minus; D2 &divide; 100)
  </div>
  <p>Effective combined discount:</p>
  <div class="formula-box">
    Effective Discount = 1 &minus; (1 &minus; D1 &divide; 100) &times; (1 &minus; D2 &divide; 100)
  </div>
  <p>Where:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>D1</strong> = first discount percentage</li>
    <li><strong>D2</strong> = second discount percentage</li>
  </ul>
  <p>The key insight: stacked discounts <strong>multiply</strong>, they don't add. 30% + 15% is not 45% off — it's 40.5% off, because the second discount applies to the already-reduced price.</p>
</section>

<!-- ── EXAMPLE ── -->
<section class="content-section reveal">
  <h2>Example</h2>

  <div class="example-box">
    <h4>Jacket on sale with an extra coupon</h4>
    <p>You find an $89.99 jacket marked 30% off. At checkout, you have an extra 15% coupon that stacks on top.</p>

    <div class="example-data">
      <div class="example-row"><span class="label">Original price</span><span class="value">$89.99</span></div>
      <div class="example-row"><span class="label">First discount (30%)</span><span class="value">&minus;$27.00</span></div>
      <div class="example-row"><span class="label">Price after 30% off</span><span class="value">$63.00</span></div>
      <div class="example-row"><span class="label">Second discount (15%)</span><span class="value">&minus;$9.45</span></div>
      <div class="example-row"><span class="label">Final price</span><span class="value">$53.55</span></div>
      <div class="example-row"><span class="label">Total saved</span><span class="value">$36.44</span></div>
      <div class="example-row"><span class="label">Effective discount</span><span class="value">40.5% (not 45%)</span></div>
    </div>

    <p>The second discount applies to $63.00, not the original $89.99 — that's why the effective discount is 40.5%, not 45%.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ── FAQ ── -->
<section class="content-section reveal">
  <h2>FAQ</h2>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
      How to calculate 30% off?
      <span class="faq-chevron">▼</span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-answer">
      <div class="faq-answer-inner">
        Multiply the price by 0.70. For example, 30% off $80 = $80 &times; 0.70 = $56. The quick trick: subtract the discount percentage from 100, move the decimal two places left, and multiply. 30% off → multiply by 0.70.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
      Do discounts stack by adding?
      <span class="faq-chevron">▼</span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-answer">
      <div class="faq-answer-inner">
        No — discounts multiply, they don't add. A 30% discount followed by a 15% discount is not 45% off. The second discount applies to the already-reduced price. The effective combined discount is 40.5%. This is true for all stacked discounts, coupons, and sequential markdowns.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
      What is a double discount?
      <span class="faq-chevron">▼</span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-answer">
      <div class="faq-answer-inner">
        A double discount is when two separate discounts are applied sequentially to the same item. Common examples: a sale price plus an additional coupon, an employee discount on top of a clearance price, or "extra 20% off all sale items." The order doesn't matter — 30% then 15% gives the same result as 15% then 30%.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
      Why is the effective discount less than the sum?
      <span class="faq-chevron">▼</span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-answer">
      <div class="faq-answer-inner">
        Because the second discount applies to the already-reduced price, not the original. When you take 30% off first, the price drops to 70% of the original. Then 15% off that reduced amount removes 15% of 70%, which is only 10.5% of the original. So the total is 30% + 10.5% = 40.5%, not 30% + 15% = 45%.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

